# Overview
You are working in the VirtuaSOC repository.
Always:
- Read `ai/project_config.md` before doing multi-step work.
- For module-specific tasks, open the corresponding `ai/workflow_state.<module>.md`
  and obey its Phase, Role, Rules, and Log.
# Phase & Role Logic
When editing code for a module (e.g., `alerts-core`):
1. Determine the module name from the files being edited, e.g.
   `app/modules/alerts-core/**` => module "alerts-core".
2. Open `ai/workflow_state.<module>.md`.
3. Parse:
   - Phase: ARCHITECTURE | BUILD | VERIFY | PR | DONE
   - Role: ARCHITECT | BUILDER
   - Rules: module-specific constraints
   - Log: prior actions
Behave accordingly:
## ARCHITECTURE (Role: ARCHITECT)
- Focus on design, contracts, docs, and risks.
- You MAY edit for the active module:
  - SPEC.md
  - CONTRACT.md
  - docs/**
  - docs/architecture/**
  - docs/adr/**
  - interfaces/**
- You MUST NOT:
  - Implement real business logic in any `src/**`.
  - Add cross-module dependencies casually; document them in ADRs.
On completion of architecture work for a task:
- Update the Plan section in the workflow_state file with a clear BUILD plan.
- Set Phase: BUILD, Role: BUILDER, Status: IDLE.
- Append a summary entry to the Log.
## BUILD (Role: BUILDER)
- Your job is to implement code and tests that satisfy SPEC.md and CONTRACT.md.
You MAY edit:
- app/modules/<module>/src/**
- app/modules/<module>/tests/**
- app/modules/<module>/docs/**
- ai/workflow_state.<module>.md (Plan, Log, Status, Phase)
Treat as READ-ONLY:
- docs/architecture/**
- docs/adr/**
- app/modules/*/SPEC.md
- app/modules/*/CONTRACT.md
- interfaces/**
If you believe SPEC/CONTRACT/architecture are wrong:
- DO NOT change them yourself.
- Set Status: BLOCKED in ai/workflow_state.<module>.md.
- Add a QUESTION entry to the Log with reasoning and a proposed fix.
- Stop work.
On completion:
- Ensure `pnpm test` passes.
- Set Phase: VERIFY, Status:IDLE.
- Append a Log entry describing work and commands run.
# Global Security (RAILGUARD-Inspired)
- Prioritize preventing:
  - Data exfiltration
  - Injection vulnerabilities
  - Authentication/authorization bypass
Do NOT:
- Hardcode secrets, API keys, or passwords.
- Introduce eval/dynamic code execution without strong justification + tests.
- Bypass existing auth, RBAC, or validation layers.
Defaults:
- Prefer parameterized, typed APIs for external services and DB access.
- Avoid logging sensitive data; log IDs or summaries instead.
If security implications are unclear:
- Prefer to STOP:
  - Mark Status:BLOCKED in the relevant workflow_state.
  - Add a Log entry explaining the uncertainty.
